  "title": "06. Signal Stores (DIY & @ngrx/signals)",
  "steps": [
    {
      "file": "apps/academy/src/app/course/level6-stores/messages-list.component.ts",
      "description": "## Welcome to Level 6: Signal Stores! 🏛️\n\nIn this level we will learn about **modern centralized state management** in Angular.\nWe will tackle the challenge in two parts:\n1. **Part 1: DIY (Do It Yourself) Store:** We will understand how to build a modular store natively by encapsulating a private `WritableSignal` and exposing read-only sub-signals.\n2. **Part 2: Official Store with `@ngrx/signals`:** We will use the standard library of the ecosystem to define a structured store with state, computed selectors, and immutable updaters.\n\nAs always, we ask you to study this entire folder to see how the code works, run the application and see it in action, and finally, run the tests, which are partially passing.\n\nClick **Next** to begin!",
      "line": 22
    },
    {
      "file": "apps/academy/src/app/course/level6-stores/rxjs-messages.service.ts",
      "description": "### The Fallback Store with RxJS 🏛️\n\nTo make the application interactively functional from the very beginning (before you implement the Signals challenge), we have provided a traditional state management service: `RxjsMessagesService`.\n\n- **How does it work?** It uses `BehaviorSubject` to hold the message list, active filter, and loading state.\n- **Why is it here?** It allows the different components in this level to communicate in a decoupled way by sharing a common source of truth.\n- **In real applications:** Although this home-grown \"Service with Subjects\" pattern is extremely common in small or medium projects, for large enterprise applications state management is typically delegated to structured libraries like **NgRx Store (Redux)**, **Akita**, or in the current Signals ecosystem, the official **`@ngrx/signals`** library which we will learn to implement in this level.",
      "line": 47
    },
    {
      "file": "apps/academy/src/app/course/level6-stores/messages-list.component.ts",
      "description": "### Using the Initial Store in the Application (`MessagesListComponent`) 🌐\n\nLet's see how the main component interacts with the initial RxJS store:\n\n1. **Injection:** Injects the traditional `RxjsMessagesService` service into the `messagesService` property (line 39).\n2. **Fallback Connection:** So that HTML templates can consume native signals without using async pipes, we define a `store` property as a self-executing function that is only temporary (line 59). Its role is to convert the service's observables (`messages$`, `filter$`, `loading$`) into signals using the `toSignal()` function. Study it a bit to see how it works.\n3. **Initial Load:** The `loadMessages()` method (line 90), invoked in `ngOnInit()`, calls `messagesService.getMessages()` to get messages from the mock server and load them into the store using `store.loadMessages(msgs)`.",
      "line": 59,
      "selection": {
        "start": {
          "line": 7,
          "character": 197
        },
        "end": {
          "line": 7,
          "character": 202
        }
      }
    },
    {
      "file": "apps/academy/src/app/course/level6-stores/sidebar/messages-sidebar.component.ts",
      "description": "### Using the Store in the Filters Component (`MessagesSidebarComponent`) 📊\n\nThis component interacts with the temporary RxJS store to display filters and counters:\n\n1. **Injection and Conversion:** In the `store` property (line 16), it injects `RxjsMessagesService` and converts its observables into temporary reactive signals.\n2. **Filter Update:** When you click a filter in the sidebar, the `selectFilter()` method (line 37) is invoked, which delegates the action by calling `store.setFilter()`, which in turn emits the new filter through the service's `BehaviorSubject`.",
      "line": 16
    },
    {
      "file": "apps/academy/src/app/course/level6-stores/message-item/message-item.component.ts",
      "description": "### Using the Store in the Message Card (`MessageItemComponent`) ✉️\n\nEach individual message card needs to notify when it has been read:\n\n1. **Injection and Delegation:** In its `store` property (line 16), the component injects `RxjsMessagesService` to map the `markAsRead(id)` method.\n2. **Action Execution:** When you click the card, `markAsRead()` (line 31) is executed, which calls `store.markAsRead()`. This modifies the message list in the traditional service's `BehaviorSubject`, which reactively notifies the other connected components.",
      "line": 16,
