    {
      "file": "apps/academy/src/app/course/level6-stores/messages-store.ts",
      "description": "### CHALLENGE 0: DIY Store (Do It Yourself) 🛠️\n\nLet's review the custom hand-made `CustomStore` container which is used inside the interface, in the box that reads \"State Value in CustomStore\". Its use is purely pedagogical to learn the foundations of a Store:\n1. The `private _state` property is initialized as a mutable `signal` containing the `initialState`.\n2. The `readonly state` property is public and computed: `computed(() => this._state())` made to protect the state from direct modifications from the outside.\n3. An `update(fn)` method is defined to call `this._state.update(fn)` in an immutable way.\n\n*Code Hint:*  \n```typescript\nexport class CustomStore<T> {\n  private _state = signal<T>(initialState);\n  readonly state = computed(() => this._state());\n  update(fn: (state: T) => T): void {\n    this._state.update(fn);\n  }\n}\n```",
      "line": 14
    },
    {
      "file": "apps/academy/src/app/course/level6-stores/messages-store.ts",
      "description": "### CHALLENGE 1: Store Declaration with signalStore() 🏛️\n\nFor Part 2, we will use `@ngrx/signals`.\n\n1. Define and export the constant `MessagesStore` using the `signalStore()` function.\n2. Configure the store to be injectable application-wide by passing `{ providedIn: 'root' }` as the first argument.\n\n*Code Hint:*  \n```typescript\nexport const MessagesStore = signalStore(\n  { providedIn: 'root' },\n  // ... subsequent steps\n);\n```",
      "line": 57
    },
    {
      "file": "apps/academy/src/app/course/level6-stores/messages-store.ts",
      "description": "### CHALLENGE 2: State Initialization with withState() 📦\n\nAdd the initial state property to your `signalStore()`.\n\n**What is and what does `withState` do?**\nIt is a function provided by `@ngrx/signals` used to initialize and declare the state properties of a Store. By passing it an object with the initial state (for example, `initialState`), `@ngrx/signals` automatically generates a read-only reactive signal (`Signal`) for each property of that object (in this case, `messages()`, `filter()`, and `loading()`). This allows components to consume and reactively subscribe to these state slices without additional setup.\n\n1. Use `withState(initialState)` to initialize the Store properties:\n   - `messages`: An empty array of academic messages.\n   - `filter`: The initial filter set to `'all'`.\n   - `loading`: Boolean set to `false` to track network requests.\n\n*Code Hint:*  \n```typescript\nwithState(initialState)\n```",
      "line": 58
    },
    {
      "file": "apps/academy/src/app/course/level6-stores/messages-store.ts",
      "description": "### CHALLENGE 3: Deriving Computed States with withComputed() 🧠\n\nA professional store must expose efficient reactive selectors that automatically derive information from the primary state.\n\n1. Add the `withComputed()` function to your store.\n2. Declare `unreadCount`: A `computed` that returns the number of messages with `read: false`.\n3. Declare `filteredMessages`: A `computed` that filters the message list reactively according to the value of `filter()` ('all' or 'unread').\n\n*Code Hint:*  \n```typescript\nwithComputed((store) => ({\n  unreadCount: computed(() => store.messages().filter(m => !m.read).length),\n  filteredMessages: computed(() => {\n    const filter = store.filter();\n    const messages = store.messages();\n    return filter === 'unread' ? messages.filter(m => !m.read) : messages;\n  })\n}))\n```",
      "line": 45
    },
    {
      "file": "apps/academy/src/app/course/level6-stores/messages-store.ts",
      "description": "### CHALLENGE 4: Immutable Update Methods with withMethods() and patchState() ⚡\n\nTo modify the state in `@ngrx/signals`, we define controlled methods that use the pure `patchState()` function to safely perform immutable updates.\n\n1. Add `withMethods()` to your store.\n2. Define the following updaters:\n   - `loadMessages(messages)`: Sets the academic messages and deactivates the loading state.\n   - `setFilter(filter)`: Updates the active display filter.\n   - `markAsRead(messageId)`: Maps the message collection and sets `read: true` on the corresponding message.\n   - `setLoading(loading)`: Sets the loading state of the asynchronous channel.\n\n*Code Hint:*  \n```typescript\nwithMethods((store) => ({\n  loadMessages(messages: Message[]) {\n    patchState(store, { messages, loading: false });\n  },\n  setFilter(filter: 'all' | 'unread') {\n    patchState(store, { filter });\n  },\n  markAsRead(messageId: string) {\n    patchState(store, (state) => ({\n      messages: state.messages.map(m => m.id === messageId ? { ...m, read: true } : m)\n    }));\n  },\n  setLoading(loading: boolean) {\n    patchState(store, { loading });\n  }\n}))\n```\n*(Make sure to remove the dummy declaration `export const MessagesStore: any = null;` when finished!)*",
      "line": 48
    },
    {
      "file": "apps/academy/src/app/course/level6-stores/messages-list.component.ts",
      "description": "### BONUS CHALLENGE 1: Injection in the Main Container (`MessagesListComponent`) 🌐\n\nThe container component is responsible for initiating data requests and coordinating the initial loading state.\n\n1. Inject the store instance using the injector function:\n   ```typescript\n   protected store = inject(MessagesStore);\n   ```\n2. Replace the fallback initialization block `store: any = (() => { ... })();` (from line 59 to 88) with this direct declaration. You will see how drastically the fallback boilerplate code is reduced!\n3. Observe in `ngOnInit()` (line 90) how the store methods are invoked directly and in a typed manner: `this.store.setLoading(true)` and `this.store.loadMessages(msgs)`.",
      "line": 59
    },
    {
      "file": "apps/academy/src/app/course/level6-stores/sidebar/messages-sidebar.component.ts",
      "description": "### BONUS CHALLENGE 2: Reactive Consumption in the Sidebar (`MessagesSidebarComponent`) 📊\n\nThe sidebar component needs to read reactive information (filtered messages and the unread count) and trigger filter changes.\n\n1. Open `messages-sidebar.component.ts` and inject the single global store instance into the `store` property:\n   ```typescript\n   protected store = inject(MessagesStore);\n   ```\n2. Replace the entire fallback block (lines 16 to 35) with the direct injection.\n3. Open `messages-sidebar.component.html`. Observe how we consume the derived signals exposing `store.unreadCount()` to render the counter, and `store.filter()` to determine which button is active. We also call `store.setFilter()` when clicking the buttons.",
      "line": 16
    },
    {
      "file": "apps/academy/src/app/course/level6-stores/message-item/message-item.component.ts",
      "description": "### BONUS CHALLENGE 3: Mutation Execution in the Message Card (`MessageItemComponent`) ✉️\n\nEach list item is rendered by `MessageItemComponent`. This component needs to mark the message as read when the user clicks.\n\n1. Open `message-item.component.ts` and inject the store into the `store` property:\n   ```typescript\n   protected store = inject(MessagesStore);\n   ```\n2. Replace the fallback initialization block (lines 16 to 29) with the direct injection.\n3. Observe the `markAsRead()` method (line 31): when triggered, it executes `this.store.markAsRead(this.message().id)`. This immutably updates the global messages array in the store. When doing so, the sidebar recalculates `unreadCount()` and updates the counter immediately, without needing to emit events to the parent or pass inputs. It is the magic of centralized state with Signals!",
      "line": 16
    },
    {
      "file": "apps/academy/src/app/course/level6-stores/messages-list.component.spec.ts",
      "description": "### TDL Verification! 🧪\n\n1. Run the test command: `pnpm test:l6` in the console.\n2. Vitest will validate the immutable reactivity, the store computed variables, and the semantic AST integrity.\n\nWhen all tests shine in **GREEN**, your implementation of large-scale state management will be perfect! 🚀",
      "line": 1
    }
  ]
